defaultFood security is a broad theme which encapsulates challenges to Governments and society over a wide range of topics.  It links to global agricultural production and markets, competitiveness, population growth, poverty, env
defaultironmental impacts and technological developments. Activities across 
defaultG
defaultovernment and internationally are trying to address these challenges. They are challenges that cannot be addressed by the UK alone, but rather by the UK as part of an international commu
defaultnity. 
default2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe 2011 Government Office for Science’s Foresight Report, ‘The Future of Food and Farming’ explored the increasing pressures on the global food system between now and 2050, and asked how a future global population of 9 billion people can all be fed
default healthily and sustainably.
default 
defaultIt stated that o
defaultn the demand side, global population size will increase from nearly seven billion today to eight billion by 2030, and probably to over nine billion by 2050; many people are likely to be wealthier, creating demand
default for a more varied, high-quality diet requiring additional resources to produce. On the production side, competition for land, water and energy will intensify
default.
default 
defaultRecent FAO projections state that globally
default, 
defaultdemand for food is expected to increase by around 38
default% by 2030 and by 60% by 2050
default.
default3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe
default Foresight
default report 
defaultidentified factors increasing pressure on finite land and marine resources
default -
default which include climate change, demographic shifts, changing patterns of work, and habitation
default - 
defaultthat wil
defaultl create major challenges and intensify the demands we make on our land and seas. 
