default&#xa0;defaultBiofuelsdefault16.
default&#xa0; 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the context of rising demand
default, 
defaultand against the backdrop of future climate change, biofuel policies have been cited as potentially increasing risks to food security.  The Government believes that the primary goal of agriculture must be food production and that the production of biomass f
defaultor bioenergy must not undermine food security in the UK or internationally. 
default&#xa0;
default17.
default&#xa0; 
defaultTo the extent that biofuels and biomass policies result in an increase in aggregate demand for agricultural feedstocks and/or agricultural land, they will result in higher agricu
defaultltural product prices over the medium term than would have otherwise been the case.
default 
defaultRecent analysis by Defra’s modelling team suggests biofuels support at the EU level could have a medium-term price impact on feedstocks used for biofuels production. Averag
defaulte EU wheat and oilseed prices are projected to be 5% and 17% higher than without EU biofuel policy with knock on impacts downstream in the vegetable oil market. This is broadly consistent with modelling by others.
default 
default&#xa0;
default18.
default&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthere is a distinct question about the 
defaultextent to which biofuel policies have contributed to recent international agricultural price spikes. 
defaultA
default thorough cross-Whitehall analysis of the agricultural price spikes of 2007/8 concluded that biofuels had a relatively small contribution in 2008, particu
defaultlarly as far as wheat was concerned. However, that report also raised a question about the impact of biofuel support policies on the volatility of international prices. 
default&#xa0;
default19.
default&#xa0; 
defaultI
defaultn the Government’s 2012 Bioenergy strategy
default, 
defaultwe explored mechanisms for mitigating ag
defaultricultural price spikes through introducing flexibility into biofuels mandates or other measures
default. This work reveal
defaulted
default the significant potential associated with a mechanism that allows market forces to direct grain between biofuels, animal feed and food markets during a temporary supply shortage and price spike. The report did not examine specifically the implications of 
defaultthis idea for
default bioenergy markets and stopped short of examining a particular mechanism. We are considering further work to appraise the merits of more specific proposals. 
