default&#xa0;
defaultProductivitydefault&#xa0;default21.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe CAP, trade barriers and biofuels policy all matter because of their direct impacts on food prices.  They also matter because of their impact (along with, for example, R&amp;D) on agricultural productivity.  
defaultR
defaultecent Defra 
defaultmodelling demonstrates the potential benefits
default of agricultural productivity
default.  Assuming that efficiency and productivity improvements in the EU express themselves as yield improvements, and that annual yield improvements were to be double 
defaulttheir current (rela
defaulttively low) 
defaultlevel,
default the impact on EU 
defaultagricultural prices relative to a 2020 baseline would be significant: 18% lower for wheat, 31% lower for coarse grains (maize and barley), 16% lower for beef and veal, 9% lower for both poultry and pork, 21% lower for m
defaultilk and butter, and 19% lower for cheese. 
defaultIn 
defaultall of the commodities referred to, both the EU production figures and net trade position would also be higher/better than the 2020 baseline projections. The estimated impact on 2020 prices (as well as 
defaultproduction and the trade balance) is even more significant for grains and meat, if instead one assumes that the EU12 close the current productivity gap with the EU15 by 2020.
default&#xa0;
default22.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWhilst it may be difficult to model precisely the productivity impact of any giv
defaulten policy reform, it is clear that modest improvements in productivity result in tangible improvements in consumer prices. 
defaultA
defaultgricultural productivity matters for a whole range of reasons, including food security.
default&#xa0;defaultCommon Fisheries Policydefault (CFP)default23.
default&#xa0; 
defaultFishing at su
defaultstainable levels, and removing the waste of discarding, will allow us to maximise the yield we can take from our seas in the long term, providing a more stable supply of fish to EU consumers.  Growing populations, growing demand for protein, and growing aw
defaultareness of the problems facing the marine environment should provide real opportunities to market and profit from stocks that are managed well.
default24.
default&#xa0; 
defaultEU Member States reached agreement to a historic deal to reform the 
defaultCFP
default in June this year.  Despite a difficult 
defaultand protracted negotiation, the UK stood firm on its key priorities, securing a robust ban on the discarding of fish with binding timelines, a process for regionalised decision-making, and legally binding commitments to fish sustainably. 
default25.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThese reforms are
default expected to become law from January 2014, and will benefit fishermen, the food supply chain, and the marine environment.  The reforms agreed provide a crucial opportunity to overcome the failings of the past and put the CFP on a sustainable footing, safeg
defaultuarding the supply of fish to UK and EU markets for future generations
default.
default 
default26.
default&#xa0; 
defaultImprovements to the CFP’s external dimension will also ensure we apply the same principles of sustainability outside EU waters as within.  Europe is the world’s biggest fisheries mark
defaultet and can play a vital role in the global governance of fish stocks and delivering a sustainable future. 
