default defaultThe implications of volatility in thdefaulte global food supply and demand for UK food securitydefaultKey points:defaultDetail:defaultAgriculturaldefault commodity marketsdefault40.
default&#xa0; 
defaultPrice volatility is an inherent characteristic of global agricultural commodity markets and has long characterised them. This is due to the dependence of production on weather patterns, the relative insensitivity of demand to food price changes, and produc
defaulttion lags.  
default41.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSome degree of price volatility is therefore normal but volatility tends to be highest in ‘thin’ international markets where a small proportion of global production is traded (
defaulte.g.
default, the global rice market) or when there are adverse policy resp
defaultonses to market developments such as export bans. 
defaultHowever historic attempts to manage price levels and/or reduce price volatility have been unsuccessful.
default42.
default&#xa0; 
defaultDespite the agricultural price spikes experienced in 2007/8 and more recently, there is little evidenc
defaulte to suggest that price volatility has increased over time. Indeed, analysis for the Foresight report concluded that agricultural price volatility over the two most recent decades has generally been lower than in the 1970s and 1980s. Furthermore, it should
default be noted that spikes seen in the early 1970s were far larger in real terms (i.e. accounting for inflation) than recent spikes. 
default43.
default&#xa0; 
defaultHowever there is a risk that price volatility (and the frequency of price spikes) could increase in the future, mainly due to m
defaultore volatile energy prices and extreme weather events associated with climate change. Conversely, increased trade between countries, deeper international markets for agricultural goods and the avoidance of adverse policy responses should act to reduce futu
defaultre price volatility.
default44.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIt is important to bear in mind that the volatility (and level) of commodity prices is of more importance to consumers in developing countries than in developed countries. This is firstly because poorer individuals spend a much greate
defaultr proportion of their income on food, and secondly because in developed countries the price of food to consumers is often only weakly connected to the cost of basic commodities, with other inputs like energy, labour and packaging being more important. For 
defaultexample, the price of wheat accounts for only 11% of the cost of a loaf of bread in the UK. 
default45.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAlthough commodity prices are only weakly related to the 
defaultlevel
default of some prices, modelling
default demonstrates that alongside exchange rates and oil prices, they are the l
defaultargest drivers of 
defaultinflation
default in retail food prices. 
default46.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWhilst global commodity markets have significant impacts on retail food price inflation, there is a lag between commodity price rises and their impact on retail food price inflation if for example, there 
defaultmay be contracts in place which prevent the full price increase being immediately passed on. Given that: contracts may be of differing lengths; price changes of different commodities are not perfectly correlated; and that there are other, non-commodity pri
defaultce factors driving food price inflation, then any volatility on commodities markets will be significantly moderated before their transmission to consumer prices.   
defaultSpeculationdefault47.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Government recognises that there is a range of views in respect of the role
default that may have been played by commodity speculation in recent food p
defaultrice spikes. On balance, reliable evidence suggests
default scepticism that speculation in agricultural futures markets has played a significant causal role in agricultural price volatility. However, the Government continues to monitor relevant research with interest. 
default48.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIt is also important to note that trading in 
defaultcommodity markets plays an important role in providing liquidity in these markets and that liquidity is essential to the effective functioning of these markets. Against the backdrop of climate change, and the possibility that international agricultural pri
defaultces may become more volatile over time, the role of agricultural futures and options markets and the liquidity they rely on, become more important.
defaultVolatility and developing countriesdefault49.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe UK Government recognises the damaging impact of high food prices and
default food price volatility on poor consumers in developing countries.
default 
defaultHigh price volatility reduces the benefits of higher prices for net producers. For food producing households, price volatility makes the returns to increased production more uncertain and so
default acts as a disincentive to further investment.
default 
defaultDfID and Defra are planning research to better understand the extent to which commodity price changes impact on consumers, producers and poverty in the developing world.
default50.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe UK Government believes that free tr
defaultade and effective and efficient markets provide a greater level of food security than large-scale, public food stocks designed to manage price volatility at national or international level. Experience to date suggests such stocks are expensive to run, with
default implications for fiscal positions, and are likely to crowd out private sector stocking initiatives and would therefore not necessarily stabilise prices. D
defaultf
defaultID supports, in principle, proposals for regional emergency humanitarian food stocks in high risk re
defaultgions such as the Sahel, to improve the speed and effectiveness of the 
defaultresponse to humanitarian disasters. Carefully targeted social safety nets are also important to help poor consumers in developing countries cope with price inflation.
default51.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe UK Government 
defaultis working internationally, particularly with other members of the G20, to liberalise trade and make commodity markets function more efficiently. The Government is promoting greater sharing of information on existing stocks, and discouraging disruptive act
defaultions such as export bans, which limit supplies and drive up prices.
defaultAMISdefault52.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Agriculture Market Information System (AMIS) is a G20 initiative which seeks to improve agricultural market transparency, information sharing and facilitate policy coordination be
defaulttween major producing, exporting and importing countries. A central task is its work to develop indicators to monitor market and policy drivers that impact on global food prices and global food price volatility. The AMIS Rapid Response Forum promotes early
default discussion between countries concerning abnormal market conditions and allows for the development of shared strategies. AMIS will not necessarily prevent price increases or some level of volatility but can help improve understanding of markets and enhance
default policy coordination in times of crisis. 
default53.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAMIS has made valuable progress since it was initially set up two years ago.  The UK is an active participant in all aspects of AMIS’ work and encourages the contribution of timely and high quality data around key 
defaultindicators, such as stock levels, from all members through the Global Food Information Group.
defaultPost-2015 Development Frameworkdefault default54.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe UK Government 
defaultis pushing for an ambitious and compelling set of new global development goals to take effect when the Millenni
defaultum Development G
defaultoals
default conclude in 2015.  These are an opportunity to bring people and planet together to eradicate poverty and achieve shared prosperity
default,
default including through improved food security and nutrition, sustainable natural resource
default management
default (includ
defaulting water and energy), and good governance and effective institutions.  
defaultThe potential value and contribution of science and GM technology to UK food securitydefaultKey pointsdefault:defaultDetail:default55.
