defaultGM and emerging technologiesdefaultGenomicsdefault58.
default&#xa0; 
defaultGenomics utilises the recen
defaultt acceleration in gene sequencing technology that has been researched and pioneered in the UK. It allows marker genes to be identified that correspond to the desirable traits observed in naturally occurring varieties of crops. By applying genomics (in a wa
defaulty that was not possible a decade ago) crop varieties can be selectively developed by means of an acceleration of the natural selection process.
defaultGenetic Modificationdefault59.
default&#xa0; 
defaultFrom the scientific and other evidence it is clear that the responsible use of GM crops cou
defaultld play an important role alongside other options to help ensure food security.  This conclusion has been supported by a number of important reviews in recent years which have highlighted how science and technology, including GM, will be crucial to making 
defaultagriculture more efficient and sustainable.
default  
default60.
default&#xa0; 
defaultGM technology is already contributing to UK food security via the extensive use of imported GM livestock feed, soya in particular. 
defaultThe l
defaultivestock sector could not operate at the same level without the use of 
defaultimported supplies at prevailing prices.
default 
defaultThe majority of global soya production is now GM and this is cheaper than conventional soya.         
default61.
default&#xa0; 
defaultA major barrier to the development and use of GM crops in Europe is the operation of the relevant EU controls. The
default process for authorising GM cultivation is dysfunctional because there is no political consensus on this issue, and only one GM crop has secured EU approval since 1998. The uncertainty around the approval process has deterred GM-related investment and inno
defaultvation, denying EU farmers and consumers the benefits that would be expected to flow from this.
default 
defaultA recent European Court of Justice ruling has prompted the European Commission to call for a vote by EU Ministers on a GM insect-resistant maize variety. This w
defaultill be the first such vote since 2007 and may end the current moratorium on authorisations for GM cultivation.  
default62.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe
default negative EU situation is damaging for the future of agriculture both in Europe and in developing countries which may be influenced by it. 
defaultA
defaults
default 
defaultthe
default disparity between the EU and other parts of the world on GM uptake continues to grow, this in itself poses a potential threat to our food security. It creates the possibility for traces of non-EU approved GM material to be found in imported commoditi
defaultes like soya.  This undermines the ability to maintain orderly and cost-effective supply chains on which the UK relies.  
default63.
default&#xa0; 
defaultOutside Europe
default,
default GM production is already significant whilst in the EU only one GM crop is being grown on a limited scale (an insect-re
defaultsistant maize of no UK interest).
default 
