defaultpathogenic micro-organisms
default and safety for consumption
default, and the 
defaultFood Safety Act 1990 provides the framework for all food legislation in the UK.
default 
default75.
default&#xa0; 
defaultGovernment has a responsibility to ensure that food law is upheld and consumers are protected, but the primary obligation to ensure that f
defaultood supplied is safe to eat is placed on food businesses. Food businesses must tell the FSA where they have reason to believe that a foodstuff that they have imported, produced, manufactured or distributed does not meet food safety requirements, and must u
defaultse their own approach to exercise due diligence over the food they sell to ensure they are meeting safety and authenticity requirements.  Businesses agree specific specifications with suppliers and suppliers are subject to inspection by such businesses as 
defaultwell as local authorit
defaulties
default. Many large food businesses also conduct their own testing of food samples.
default76.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe central competent authority in the UK for monitoring and controlling the application of food law is the Food Standards Agency (FSA).  
defaultHowever, t
defaulthe maj
defaultority of surveillance and enforcement activity to protect the consumer is undertaken locally by local and port health authorities. Local authority staff routinely inspect premises on a risk basis as well as collecting samples which are tested for food safe
defaultty or compositional and labelling compliance.  In 2010-11 89% of food businesses checked were broadly compliant with food safety law.
default77.
default&#xa0; 
defaultRegulation (EC) 178/2002 lays down the EU principles and requirements of food law.  It applies to all stages of production
default, processing and distribution of food and feed.  Around one fifth of all spending to 
defaultcheck for compliance with food law is at the stage of slaughterhouses, cutting plan
defaultt
defaults and primary producers. 
defaultThis reflects EU prescription, the relatively high safety risk
default of food handling at these stages, and the need to track raw meat to the farms and suppliers for both animal and human health purposes.
default78.
default&#xa0; 
